\begin_layout Standard
Our belief of how likely an event
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 would happen is qualified by its interval-valued probability
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\mu}\left(E\right)$
\end_inset

 because we only have a bounded measurement resource.
 The natural questions would be: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If we have an infinitely measurement resource, could we tight up the interval
 and get a real-valued probability
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\mu\left(E\right)\in\left[0,1\right]$
\end_inset

? 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Does our interval-valued belief well estimate the real-valued probability?
 In particular, is the real-valued probability within the interval, i.e,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu\left(E\right)\in\bar{\mu}\left(E\right)$
\end_inset

?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When the interval-valued probability measure
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


